article.description: Tamika Catchings made five 3-pointers and finished with 18 points as Indiana beat Washington 50-45 on Saturday night.
article.headline: Catchings hits five 3-pointers in victory
article.linkText: Catchings helps Fever start homestand on right foot
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The Indiana Fever made up for their
struggling offense with some tough defense.

	   ''Our games where we play defense are the games we normally
win,'' said Tamika Catchings, who had five 3-pointers and finished
with 18 points in the Fever's 50-45 victory over Washington on
Saturday night.

	   Nikki McCray added 13 points against her former team as the
Fever (7-9) opened a WNBA-record eight-game homestand.

	   Washington (12-5) had its lowest-scoring game this season while
playing its third consecutive game without injured Chamique
Holdsclaw, the league's leading scorer and rebounder. The Mystics
also shot a season-low 34 percent from the field.

	   ''It wasn't pretty defense, but we had to have it,'' Indiana
coach Nell Fortner said.

	   ''We came out knowing what we had to do and we left it all on
the floor,'' Catchings said. ''We just hustled, muscled and
fought.''

	   Indiana shot only 32 percent, but McCray put the game out of
reach with two free throws for a 49-45 lead with 26.9 seconds
remaining.

	   Stacey Dales-Schuman led the Mystics with 13 points, and Annie
Burgess was the only other player in double figures for Washington
with 10.

	   A 3-pointer by Catchings gave Indiana its biggest lead at 43-33
with 14:27 to play. But the Fever hit only two more field goals --
none in the final six minutes -- and Washington closed to 47-45 on a
layup by Dales-Schuman with 29 seconds to go. She was fouled on the
play, but missed the free throw, and Catchings got the rebound to
McCray.

	   ''We're running a new motion offense which wears us out,''
Fortner said. ''We've only run it for one week. We need to learn
how to mix up our offense,'' Fortner said.

	   Catchings added: ''Sometimes we tend to stand around a lot and
that's what happened in the two droughts that we had -- people just
weren't moving around.''

	   The victory came one game after Indiana blew a 14-point
second-half lead and lost at Orlando 79-71.

	   ''We talked about the things that we messed up on the other
night, and kept telling each other to stay on our feet and not foul
the 3-point shooters,'' Catchings said.

	   After McCray was fouled and hit both her shots, Monica Maxwell
stole the ball for Indiana and Catchings hit 1-of-2 free throws to
end the scoring.

	   ''Our offense stalled tonight. We didn't play well together,''
Dales-Schuman said. ''The Fever were well prepared for us and
scouted us well. The culmination of the two equaled success for
them.''

	   The victory put Indiana two weeks ahead of its pace of last
season when it didn't win its seventh game until July 20 in its
21st game.
